<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910805-0066</DOCNO><DOCID>910805-0066.</DOCID><HL>   Seagate Technology   Cuts 1% of Work Force</HL><DATE>08/05/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C15</SO><CO>   SGAT</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)</IN><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)EUROPE (EU)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PORTUGAL (PO)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)WESTERN EUROPE (WEU)</RE><LP>   SCOTT'S VALLEY, Calif. -- For the second time in twoweeks, Seagate Technology Inc. shaved its payroll in aneffort to help its disk-drive business recover from recessionand price wars.   The company said it will dismiss an additional 450employees, or 1% of its work force, mainly fromnon-manufacturing jobs. Seagate also will close an operationin Portugal which assembled magnetic heads for older diskdrives.</LP><TEXT>   Seagate had terminated 1,200 employees or 3% of its workforce in mid-July as part of a restructuring designed tocounteract the effects of ferocious price cutting. After bothwaves of firings, the company will have about 40,000employees world-wide.   &quot;We hope these reductions will be sufficient to bring ouroperating expenses into line with business conditions,&quot; aspokeswoman said.   Seagate's profit in the fourth quarter ended June 30plunged 98% to $383,000,or one cent a share, from $29.7million, or 46 cents a share. Revenue rose to almost $677million from $668.1 million.</TEXT></DOC>